<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="161" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,833,1254]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,567,869,894]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Pertinent taxonomic reference.</emphasis>
Teixeira 
<emphasis box="[672,728,869,894]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">et al.</emphasis>
(2013b), Colli 
<emphasis box="[900,950,869,894]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">et al</emphasis>
. (2015), Goicoechea 
<emphasis box="[1191,1240,869,894]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">et al</emphasis>
. (2016), Ribeiro- Júnior 
<emphasis box="[228,277,905,930]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">et al</emphasis>
. (2016).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,833,1254]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1503410429" country="Brazil" location="Rondonia" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Rondonia">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,447,941,966]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
Teixeira 
<emphasis box="[557,616,941,966]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">et al.</emphasis>
(2013b) described 
<taxonomicName box="[840,993,941,966]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scaea">
<emphasis box="[840,993,941,966]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia scaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[1204,1316,941,966]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
, in 
<collectingCountry box="[1360,1431,941,966]" name="Brazil" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, based on the absence of clawed fingers, and supralabials and parietals separated by the first temporal. However, these characters were also observed by us in some specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[875,1054,1013,1038]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="peruana">
<emphasis box="[875,1054,1013,1038]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia peruana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1109,1249,1013,1038]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dorbignyi">
<emphasis box="[1109,1249,1013,1038]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">B. dorbignyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as well. For this reason we cited here 
<taxonomicName box="[417,520,1050,1073]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scaea">
<emphasis box="[417,520,1050,1073]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">B. scaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based only on type-specimens records available in Teixeira 
<emphasis box="[1262,1318,1049,1074]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">et al</emphasis>
. (2013b), considering that more studies are necessary to confirm the validity of this species.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="161" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,833,1254]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,500,1121,1146]" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[509,661,1121,1146]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="161" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scaea">
<emphasis box="[509,661,1121,1146]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Bachia scaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to southern 
<taxonomicName box="[936,1054,1121,1146]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="10" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, where it is only known from the left bank of the Madeira River in Porto Velho, state of 
<collectingRegion box="[779,891,1157,1182]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[903,971,1157,1182]" name="Brazil" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[988,1058,1157,1182]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1113,1135]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,189,1086]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,179,1091]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of examined material of Amapasaurus tetradactylus, B. panoplia, B. peruana, B. pyburni, B. remota, B. scolecoides, and B. trisanale. Records of Bachia didactyla and B. scaea were obtained from the literature." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581978/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). It is semi-fossorial and diurnal, inhabits varzea forests (seasonally flooded forest by white-water rivers, such as the Madeira River) with dense leaf litter, where it is found among the leaf litter and under rotten trunks and fallen logs (Teixeira 
<emphasis box="[1193,1242,1229,1254]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="161">et al</emphasis>
. 2013b).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
